 South African former President Jacob Zuma will stand trial on corruption charges relating to a $2.5 billion arms deal after the court denied him a permanent stay of prosecution on Friday. The ruling by Judge Jerome Mnguni in the Pietermaritzburg High Court paves way for Zuma’s trial to start on Oct. 15. Zuma, who was in office from 2009-2018, had applied for a permanent stay of prosecution from 16 charges of fraud, racketeering and money laundering relating to a deal to buy 30 billion rand of European military hardware for South Africa’s armed forces in the late 1990s. Continue reading South Africa’s Zuma to face corruption trial at Vanguard Nigeria. Source: Vanguard